data.jamchart_notes: The rhythm section keeps the pace up while Peter lays down a bright progression. The band jams on a theme akin to "Love is a Battlefield" before transitioning neatly to "Electric Avenue."
Atypical arpeggiator starts off the first headlining performance of 2023. The band vibes and gets loose within the confines of the groove before finishing "Electric Avenue" from Okeechobee.

data.footnote: Eddy Grant. Ending only, finishing the version from 3/3/23 Okeechobee.

data.jamchart_notes: Right out of the gate, the band dives into some Winter '22-style dark jamming. Peter goes to a haunting upright piano tone as he and Rick lock in. Spuds shoots the improv into a swirling vortex that transitions cleanly into some bluesy rock at Rick's urging. Organ and guitar trade riffs before Rick steers the band into three-chord bliss. Trevor really steps out on the sustained full-band peak w/ envelope filter work as the joyous peak wraps back to "AIN" proper and a second jam fakeout into "Dr. D."

data.jamchart_notes: Extra-mustard version with a Trevor Bass solo.

data.footnote: With Jive II teases from Trevor.
data.jamchart_notes: Boundary-pushing jam highlighted by Rick's dreamlike trills at 12:45 and Peter's synths at 14:58. Hazy ambient drift with no end goal, and no need for one - just totally locked in and thematic jamming: brilliant sign for the Cap & Spring Tour.

Fiery Type 1 jam breaks at 12:16 into open plane of space highlighted by Trevor Bass. A contemplative & melancholic jam emerges, bringing to mind Talk Talk and The Cure, centered around gorgeous leads from Rick & Peter before > to "Doobie."

All-time first jam that starts off with fiery Rick shredding and melts into one of the most beautiful sections of patient, double-guitar bliss you will hear. Second jam contains a funk party that ends with Loose Ends jamming.
Dark, eerie jamming (almost but not quite Crazy Train) that begins to speed up relentlessly, quiets down before the close and then returns to Rockdale out of a tension-filled frenzy.

data.footnote: With Pick Up The Pieces teases from Rick and Peter.
data.jamchart_notes: Double guitar funk, effect-filled start that takes a melodic turn as Pete switches to keys. Very cool ending as Rick finds a repeating theme he toys around as the rest of the band builds around him.
Percussive and taut jamming around the Rosewood theme leads to a hypnotic jamming segment on the backhalf when the rythm section hooks up with Rick & Peter channeling Neu! & Kraftwerk.
Haunting yet patient dark opening jam takes off in the 13th minute and never lets up again. Melodic happiness ensues (with Loose Ends teases) and continues to build into peak after glorious peak.

data.jamchart_notes: The sun beats down as the galleon plods rhythmically through the gentle open ocean. An alarm cry from the crows nest. The quiet sea begins to boil as the terrible mecha phoenix of the Enemy rises from the water and into the sky. Cries of terror and resignation as the creature bursts aflame and slams its wings into the hull in a furious rage, capsizing and igniting the vessel as the horribly blackened crew all sink lifelessly to their demise.

data.jamchart_notes: Longest jam to date. Multi-sectional behemoth. Cathartic bliss begins as band shakes off PA issues. "Loose Ends" hints lead into a deep funk "Camino" jam as TREVOR BASS makes the filth even filthier. From there, Rick leads into a segment similar to "SOS" or the "Crosseyed and Painless" intro jam as Peter warms up on Vibe. A final pivot into a long, evil build similar to the Philly "Echo" with some foot-guitar action from Peter explodes back into the song. Fully engaging throughout.

data.jamchart_notes: A serious triumph for fans of patient and psychedelic Goose. Everyone hangs back and just chills in the space as Rick influences with heavy delay and echo loops. Peter soaks it all up with thick Vintage Vibe works as the rhythm section holds it all down. Increases in intensity yet remains calm through a haze of synthesizer and Goedde's light curtain. Unreal.

Getting 2nd set opener treatment, jam turns darker and more exploratory than we’ve seen from "Empress" to date after typical rocking start. After soaking in this space, Ben goes double time and Pete turns on lasers for shredding alien abduction.
Gentle, delicate start that patiently builds to wonderful soaring peak before beautifully melting away into "Peggy-O."
Clav-driven funk to start and finishing with fire, this version is a raging, emphatic ending to an unbelievable stretch of music that began with "Borne."

data.jamchart_notes: Another notch in the belt of the early '23 "Borne" dominance. The must-hear jam starts out minimalistic and hypnotic, similar to the Eugene version. Peter pushes the band out of the murkiness and into some dark jamming which leads to a hair-raising and triumphant peak.

A jam that Peter would write home about, two guitar Goose locks in immediately. Peter finds a nasty repeating hook at 14:20 that band centers and builds around. In 19th minute, band cools jam down and a few minutes later Peter begins soloing melodically and beautifully on the keys. Goose slowly and magically builds around Pete once again and finishes in gorgeous fashion.

data.jamchart_notes: Second big Boston "E or A?" of 2023. Jam begins to break into space with some octave-up from rick and reverb-drenched marimba from Peter, though still anchored in the song's progression. Second half hits double-time and explodes outward into a sunny afternoon of a peak. Just nonstop momentum.

Dark and synthy. Learning lessons from each version on the road to Boston, this one has some amazing eerie texturing from Peter, while Rick and Trevor growl in the darkness. Gradually picks up steam with the same ominous Prophet synth undertone throughout. Excellent display of tension-building here.

An important stop on the journey to the insanity at Red Rocks in just a few weeks, we are treated to another dive into Vintage Vibe darkness as the rhythm section holds down a beautiful bedrock for Rick and Peter to weave around each other. Run through a brick wall with the momentum of this one.

data.jamchart_notes: Whether you think it's the JOTY or not, this "Thatch" is a seriously dense listen. Dark and percussive at first, it feels very typical for the tour but quickly heads into evil territory thanks to Rick and Peter's interplay. Spuds pivots into a charging beat at the 18th minute and they just go for it. Superlatives can't even do this peak justice - needs to be listened. Rick plays with his Whammy at the apex before they execute a perfect and towering return to the song proper. All-timer.

data.jamchart_notes: The third festival "Kylie" of the year breaks from form in an amazing "Elmeg the Wise"-like jam. Triumph.
Eschews the usual blistering and fast-paced jam in favour of a laid-back and major-key space. Shorter version that will draw you in for repeated listens.

Peppy jam begins with Spuds on punchy tom work as Peter lays into the Vibe. Turns spacey and then falls away into a bouncy funk jam that feels totally unique to Goose's sound. Trevor and Rick lock in on some riffs while Peter moves to a textural role throughout the contemplative and unhurried groove. Must-listen to understand the developmental period of Fall '23.

data.jamchart_notes: Newly rearranged "EMG" jam segment is perfectly suited to the pure evil that develops at Red Rocks. Locking in on a theme like the hallowed 1/30/22 "Wysteria" and 6/10/22 "AIN," Rick just doesn't let up for a second as Spuds and Jebb go wild on the primal drums. Trevor drops massive bombs as Peter hammers piano chords and the darkness just BUILDS. Absolutely astounding improv.
Closes the first set like its recent counterpart in Oakland. Gets outside of standard "Yeti" for some fun peak jamming.
Continuation of the mellower and more upbeat "Thatch" style seen at the Wiltern on 9/28. Rocking first half transitions into a quieter space that builds into an excellent peak.

This top shelf "Factory Fiction" jam begins with a snarling slow burn. Eventually finding its way into a patiently developed anthemic Rick-led "Dragonfly" jam, this sonic assault on the alien landscape of Red Rocks concludes in an explosive fashion that merits repeat listens.

Eventually hits a blistering peak and returns home.

data.jamchart_notes: Highlight of the Jamsterdam show, Peter shines as he drives mood of jam with simple yet powerful selections on keys throughout, ending in beautiful Blissteria collective band magic. Slides into a really great "Electric Avenue."
Eugene "Borne"-style jamming for the middle few minutes as the band gets atypically quiet and patient. Layers of textures are absolutely breathtaking and it's a shame it's so short!
Peter collects a bunch of coins early on as the rhythm section destroys the minimalist funk groove. Rick pivots into triumph and the band unleashes a volcanic peak to close it out.

data.jamchart_notes: Longest "Lee" to date doesn't go too far from home, at least initially, as Peter dials up some synth undertones. Hits on some "Dragonfly" elements before Spuds takes control as he was wont to do on the Europe '23 tour. Peter plays with motif's almost like Vulfpeck's "Tee Time" as Rick shreds up to the finish.

data.jamchart_notes: Free-flowing, collective no-one-take-the-lead improv as you can find little moments throughout where any 2 band members riff of each other only to have the others join in. Gradual, patient build leading to explosive peak.

Quickly heads for Winter 2022-style dark jamming. Trevor gets DEEP into Spuds' pocket as Rick's angular soloing swirls around Peter's eerie piano. Synths come in as it gets heavier and into some carnival-like zones before the band bails back into the "Echo" ending.

data.footnote: With Within You Without You tease from Peter.

data.jamchart_notes: Immediately dropping into a darker key akin to the Red Rocks version, this jam pulsates and is driven forward by ferocious drumming, slowly building to majestic glorious rock.

data.footnote: Prince. With Axel F teases from Rick.

data.jamchart_notes: After funky start where Luigi finds his coins, Peter layers mystical synths and Rick finds a haunting repeating riff that propels a wonderfully unique and enchanting version. Thrilling finish.

Blistering Type I play cools into a brief "Shama" fakeout before Goose unleashes one of the best bliss jams in recent memory. Calling to mind the Cap "Drive," each member takes their time with the theme and delivers an absolutely incredible peak.

After Peter tells crowd they have one more song, Rick rips back into a second Drive jam to end the show. A fiery theme develops and eventually morphs into the "(dawn)" finish. Incredible spontaneous moment.

data.jamchart_notes: Peter stays on guitar for the entire jam, an exceptionally rare occurrence for the time period. Some nasty Type I churn explodes through the first part of the jam but cools around 13:30. Peter's staccato repeated riff informs the next part of the jam, where the band plays with a theme akin to the ending of "Dripfield." Great upbeat groove modes.

data.jamchart_notes: “DDS”/“The Doctor Will See You Now” vocal shenanigans lead to gorgeous bliss. Ben eventually hits double time and jam builds to soaring, beautiful first climax. In 16th minute, they return to traditional "Madhuvan" rocking. Peter takes lead with a few playful piano solos before Rick storms back in for an another blistering peak. Just when you think it may be winding down in minute 21, band rips back in and explodes the finish. One of the best jams, if not the best, of Euro Tour 23.

data.jamchart_notes: Builds momentum like many '23 versions but begins to stray from normal when Peter hits the clav with some subtle delay. Spuds is an absolute WORKHORSE as he keeps the propulsive tempo up. Rick finds a melody that he likes and Goose shreds to a peak of epic proportions. Final night of tour throw-down.
